    <title>Growing Momentum for AP Credit Policies in the States</title>
    <link>https://www.collegeboard.org/membership/all-access/academic/growing-momentum-ap-credit-policies-states</link>
    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-image field-type-image field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; rel=&quot;&quot; resource=&quot;https://www.collegeboard.org/sites/default/files/styles/all_access_image_style/public/WS.130323_01_522.jpg?itok=Bhvr11MF&quot;&gt;&lt;img typeof=&quot;foaf:Image&quot; src=&quot;https://www.collegeboard.org/sites/default/files/styles/all_access_image_style/public/WS.130323_01_522.jpg?itok=Bhvr11MF&quot; alt=&quot;Growing Momentum for AP Credit Policies in the States&quot; title=&quot;Growing Momentum for AP Credit Policies in the States&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-author field-type-text field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;Jeff Peterson, Executive Director of State Government Relations, the College Board&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-newsletter-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/taxonomy/term/566&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;AP&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/all-access-tags/ap-credit-policy&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;AP credit policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/all-access-tags/ap-state-policy&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;AP state policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/taxonomy/term/551&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;Access to Opportunity&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; property=&quot;content:encoded&quot;&gt;&lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&quot;&gt;Last Thursday, Illinois Governor Bruce Rauner &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-college-credit-apclasses-met-20150814-story.html&quot;&gt;signed&lt;/a&gt; into law &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/billstatus.asp?DocNum=3428&amp;amp;GAID=13&amp;amp;GA=99&amp;amp;DocTypeID=HB&amp;amp;LegID=89613&amp;amp;SessionID=88&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;HB3428&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, legislation requiring all Illinois public colleges and universities to award credit to students who submit scores of 3 and higher on AP Exams. This applies to entering freshmen at Illinois public institutions of higher education beginning in the fall of 2016.&lt;span&gt;A statewide AP college credit policy helps ensure that public universities and colleges consistently and fairly recognize AP students’ academic achievement and simultaneously provides these institutions with an innovative solution to improve retention and decrease time to degree.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&quot;&gt;For Illinois students, families and educators, this means greater access to AP and all the opportunities that go along with it. With HB 3428 signed into law, Illinois now will have a statewide Advanced Placement credit policy ensuring that students receive the college credits they can earn as a result of their hard work in AP. At a time when AP participation and performance has increased significantly in the state, this law provides more students with a greater opportunity to graduate college on time. A bipartisan group of public officials in Illinois worked for this result, including Governor Rauner and the bill sponsors: Representatives Carol Sente and Mike Fortner and Senator Pat McGuire.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Earlier this year, the Governors of Virginia and Texas signed into law similar legislation. With the Illinois bill signing, 17 states now award college credit state-wide or system-wide to students earning scores of 3 and higher on AP Exams. Efforts are underway in other states, including in Colorado, Nevada, and Pennsylvania. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span property=&quot;dc:title&quot; content=&quot;Growing Momentum for AP Credit Policies in the States&quot; class=&quot;rdf-meta element-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</description>
